fields.review: Like Wheel of Time series, only with no magic and infused with ickiness.  Child prostitution, incest and attempted child murder all in the first 75 pages.  No thanks.
Made me want to learn more about the Pliocene, actually.
Much better than I thought it was going to be.   Reminds me of Wheel of Time.  Hopefully this series finishes in less than a dozen books, though.
I never finished this, and I don't think I ever will.
Even better than the first one in some ways, weaker ending though.

It was ok informationally, but boy was it a slog.   A lot of worrying about theological implications of a modern day Catholic Church's impact on the 17th century Catholic Church, which is only distantly academically interesting.  Frankly, a lot of talking, not much going on.
First time I've been utterly surprised in a long time.
Never finished it.  It's a regular old sci-fi plot, with a twist that doesn't work for me.

Couldn't finish it.    Rather, I wasn't interested enough to finish it.  Most of the characters are hard to sympathize with at the least and too sad to endure for long at the best.  Dylan, the main character, looked like he was constantly headed for a train wreck, and I grew tired of waiting for it to arrive.
Never finished.  I wasn't into the original, and this is simply the originals plus zombies that have no direct impact on the plot.
I kept waiting for it to get somewhere, but in vain.
Never actually finished it, but I don't think I'm going to.
I didn't actually finish this one.  The premise -- the building of Stonehenge -- was just too drawn out, and the character development was not compelling enough for me to finish the book.
I never actually finished this one because of time constraints, but I liked it.  Somewhat less than the other things I'd read by him.
I got 50 pages from the end and never finished.

I didn't finish this book, nor did my partner. This is another character driven novels in which the back story of each of the characters is so important and so complex that the overwhelming majority of the book is spent telling that backstory. As a result, I couldn't actually tell what the main plot was by 2/3 through the book.

It's not that I don't like such books; it's more that I've read so many of them; Gabriel Garcia Marquez writes much like this, as hass Salman Rushdie, Isabel Allende, etc.
